 The electron is in two places at once.

00:15:59.620 --> 00:16:01.660
 Then when we measure it,

00:16:01.660 --> 00:16:04.040
 what we're doing is getting entangled with the particle

00:16:04.040 --> 00:16:06.560
 so that we see one version of it.

00:16:06.560 --> 00:16:08.880
 And another version of us sees another version.

00:16:08.880 --> 00:16:12.560
 So version one of me sees electrons here,

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:14.840
 another version of me sees electrons over there.

00:16:14.840 --> 00:16:18.800
 And they don't interact with each other generally.

00:16:18.800 --> 00:16:20.380
 So it appears as if the other version

00:16:20.380 --> 00:16:21.680
 has disappeared from view.

00:16:21.680 --> 00:16:26.760
 But that's all something which comes out of the Schrodinger

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:28.000
 equation essentially.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:29.440
 - What collapse says is,

00:16:29.440 --> 00:16:31.080
 so we have this particle in the box.

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:32.640
 It's maybe in like two states,

00:16:32.640 --> 00:16:34.900
 like it's in a superposition of two states.

00:16:34.900 --> 00:16:36.760
 So it's kind of like in this mix of states,

00:16:36.760 --> 00:16:37.880
 like it's unclear which is which,

00:16:37.880 --> 00:16:39.820
 but there's like a, you know,

00:16:39.820 --> 00:16:41.220
 as if you were to like, you know,

00:16:41.220 --> 00:16:43.380
 mix several liquids, for example,

00:16:43.380 --> 00:16:45.880
 like it's sort of like in a mix of both states.

00:16:45.880 --> 00:16:50.880
 And when we, in the collapse approach,

00:16:50.880 --> 00:16:53.040
 like the traditional way of thinking about it,

00:16:53.040 --> 00:16:54.840
 when we look at it,

00:16:56.540 --> 00:16:59.480
 the particle will collapse into either of those states.

00:16:59.480 --> 00:17:01.880
 So states like A and B, for example,

00:17:01.880 --> 00:17:04.020
 and then, and that's why we see only A or B,

00:17:04.020 --> 00:17:06.420
 even throwing the equations, you would see A and B.

00:17:06.420 --> 00:17:07.260
 - Yes.

00:17:07.260 --> 00:17:10.240
 - And then what many worlds says is when I,

00:17:10.240 --> 00:17:13.960
 when I look at the particle, I get entangled with it.

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:15.920
 So I get, you know, connected.

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:22.060
 And that leads me to see in one branch,

00:17:22.060 --> 00:17:24.660
 we're getting through the branches,

00:17:24.660 --> 00:17:26.320
 the states, the particle in state A,

00:17:26.320 --> 00:17:29.000
 and in the other branch, in particle B,

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:32.220
 and many worlds says both of those are equally real.

00:17:32.220 --> 00:17:33.060
 Is that correct?

00:17:33.060 --> 00:17:33.880
 - Yeah, they're equally real.

00:17:33.880 --> 00:17:36.340
 And so one of the benefits of this is that we don't have

00:17:36.340 --> 00:17:40.260
 to assume different kinds of dynamics

00:17:40.260 --> 00:17:42.060
 when we're performing a measurement.

00:17:42.060 --> 00:17:43.800
 We also don't have to assume what a measurement is.

00:17:43.800 --> 00:17:47.600
 We can derive a model of what a measurement is

00:17:47.600 --> 00:17:49.120
 from the theory itself,

00:17:49.120 --> 00:17:51.500
 so that we don't have these undefined words

00:17:51.500 --> 00:17:54.820
 that we're using in setting up the theory.

00:17:56.100 --> 00:17:59.960
 And it also kind of makes sense of what it even means

00:17:59.960 --> 00:18:02.800
 for the particle to be in a superposition in the first place,

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:05.780
 because in the conventional view, it's kind of unclear.

00:18:05.780 --> 00:18:07.900
 It's not clear what it means for the particle

00:18:07.900 --> 00:18:08.820
 to be in superposition.

00:18:08.820 --> 00:18:12.240
 It just means it's either here or there kind of potentially.

00:18:12.240 --> 00:18:15.580
 - Yes, and there's a probability and it's, yeah.

00:18:15.580 --> 00:18:17.360
 - Yeah, so it's vague.

00:18:17.360 --> 00:18:19.800
 Whereas in many worlds too, it just means,

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:23.260
 well, there is, the particle really is in two places at once

00:18:23.260 --> 00:18:25.880
 and it's behaving exactly as if it is

00:18:25.880 --> 00:18:29.420
 actually here and actually there at the same time.

00:18:29.420 --> 00:18:34.420
 And that is true for things which get entangled with it as well.

00:18:34.420 --> 00:18:38.440
 So it gives a more explanatory framework

00:18:38.440 --> 00:18:41.180
 for understanding how quantum theory actually works.

00:18:41.180 --> 00:18:44.880
 So there's both the formal benefits

00:18:44.880 --> 00:18:46.700
 and then at the level of the explanation,

00:18:46.700 --> 00:18:48.100
 I feel it's much more intuitive.

00:18:48.100 --> 00:18:52.420
 So those would be some of the reasons why I like theory.

00:18:52.420 --> 00:18:55.660
 - We have those two branches now.

00:18:55.660 --> 00:18:59.320
 And what we're seeing is that those are equally real.

00:18:59.320 --> 00:19:00.920
 What does this actually imply?

00:19:00.920 --> 00:19:02.120
 Like, where are we getting to?

00:19:02.120 --> 00:19:04.280
 So there are many worlds then?

00:19:04.280 --> 00:19:05.380
 - Yes.

00:19:05.380 --> 00:19:06.480
 - Kind of like bringing it up, but.

00:19:06.480 --> 00:19:08.280
 - Yeah, it's in the name.

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:09.340
 You've got the name, right?

00:19:09.340 --> 00:19:14.340
 Yes, so there are different worlds in which,

00:19:14.340 --> 00:19:17.080
 for example, as I've said,

00:19:17.080 --> 00:19:20.080
 it could be small things which initiate the branching.

00:19:20.080 --> 00:19:23.900
 So I see particle being here instead of there.

00:19:25.440 --> 00:19:29.920
 And consequently, that kind of quantum effect gets amplified.

00:19:29.920 --> 00:19:32.300
 And now I have a record of where in my mind,

00:19:32.300 --> 00:19:34.340
 I have a record of where the particle was,

00:19:34.340 --> 00:19:36.960
 as does the environment from then on.

00:19:36.960 --> 00:19:39.640
 It could be that this information

00:19:39.640 --> 00:19:40.720
 is somehow leaked to the environment.

00:19:40.720 --> 00:19:44.200
 So maybe to make it a little bit artificial,

00:19:44.200 --> 00:19:47.100
 but let's say that I have decided

00:19:47.100 --> 00:19:52.100
 if I see the particle in state of being here,

00:19:52.100 --> 00:19:54.180
 then I'm gonna cook some dinner.

00:19:54.180 --> 00:19:55.220
 And if I see the particle here,

00:19:55.220 --> 00:19:57.280
 well, then I'm gonna read a book.

00:19:57.280 --> 00:19:58.440
 And then after a little while,

00:19:58.440 --> 00:20:00.380
 you'll see that the kitchen is messy in one branch

00:20:00.380 --> 00:20:02.880
 and it's not in the other.

00:20:02.880 --> 00:20:07.880
 And so these small differences in the state of an initial,

00:20:07.880 --> 00:20:12.140
 like just a particle, just a microscopic particle,

00:20:12.140 --> 00:20:13.640
 within that case has been amplified up

00:20:13.640 --> 00:20:15.400
 to cause a mess in the kitchen,

00:20:15.400 --> 00:20:17.060
 in one branch and not the other.

00:20:17.060 --> 00:20:18.880
 That kind of thing is constantly going on.

00:20:18.880 --> 00:20:22.780
 So there's constantly things are in superposition,

00:20:22.780 --> 00:20:25.000
 like through natural processes.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.420
 And then they happen to get measured,

00:20:27.420 --> 00:20:28.460
 where measured really in this case,

00:20:28.460 --> 00:20:30.380
 could mean just information about where the particle is,

00:20:30.380 --> 00:20:32.840
 gets encoded in the environment,

00:20:32.840 --> 00:20:35.860
 gets encoded in me, in the mind, or in other things.

00:20:35.860 --> 00:20:40.860
 And from then on, these kind of differentiating effects

00:20:40.860 --> 00:20:46.520
 percolate throughout the environment.

00:20:46.520 --> 00:20:49.420
 So there's more and more records are in the environment

00:20:49.420 --> 00:20:51.340
 of where the particle was.

00:20:51.340 --> 00:20:54.780
 And that means that more and more of the world is different,

00:20:54.780 --> 00:20:56.680
 one branch than it was in the other one.

00:20:56.680 --> 00:20:58.220
 So you get these branches,

00:20:58.220 --> 00:21:00.500
 which are initially different only in small ways,

00:21:00.500 --> 00:21:02.560
 and then they become different in larger ways.

00:21:02.560 --> 00:21:03.400
 And because of that,

00:21:03.400 --> 00:21:07.080
 it's harder and harder for them to reinterfere,

00:21:07.080 --> 00:21:08.640
 to influence each other again.

00:21:08.640 --> 00:21:11.160
 - Yeah, so it is a good way to think about it,

00:21:11.160 --> 00:21:14.360
 that it's sort of like a bubble growing of entanglements.

00:21:14.360 --> 00:21:17.400
 And so let's say, you have the particle in the box.

00:21:17.400 --> 00:21:19.420
 So I'm the observer in the laboratory.

00:21:19.420 --> 00:21:20.620
 I'm looking at the particle.

00:21:20.620 --> 00:21:21.660
 I get entangled with it

00:21:21.660 --> 00:21:24.560
 because the information reaches my eyes and my brain.

00:21:24.560 --> 00:21:26.100
 And then just all of me.

00:21:26.100 --> 00:21:29.060
 And then maybe I will open the door

00:21:29.060 --> 00:21:34.060
 and the information will reach the neighborhood around it,

00:21:34.060 --> 00:21:37.180
 and then eventually the whole world.

00:21:37.180 --> 00:21:40.200
 And so, but there is a separate version of me

00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:42.420
 that saw state B, like the particle in state B,

00:21:42.420 --> 00:21:45.260
 and that for which the same happens.

00:21:45.260 --> 00:21:46.100
 - Yes.

00:21:46.100 --> 00:21:48.400
 - And so eventually that's the process we call decoherence,

00:21:48.400 --> 00:21:52.120
 where eventually we're getting split.

00:21:52.120 --> 00:21:54.340
 And those branches are becoming

00:21:54.340 --> 00:21:57.100
 more and more separate universes,

00:21:57.100 --> 00:21:59.960
 which is, you know, what we'll call multiverse sometimes.

00:21:59.960 --> 00:22:00.800
 - Yeah.

00:22:00.800 --> 00:22:03.580
 Yeah, so the whole of physical reality

00:22:03.580 --> 00:22:05.660
 looks a bit like a collection of worlds

00:22:05.660 --> 00:22:07.140
 that we know from classical physics.

00:22:07.140 --> 00:22:08.160
 - Yes.

00:22:08.160 --> 00:22:10.840
 - They have other properties as well.

00:22:10.840 --> 00:22:14.900
 So for example, one of the things we haven't mentioned yet

00:22:14.900 --> 00:22:19.900
 is that particles and other quantum systems can interfere.

00:22:19.900 --> 00:22:21.440
 And that's one of the primary ways

00:22:21.440 --> 00:22:22.920
 that we know about quantum mechanics.

00:22:22.920 --> 00:22:24.120
 - Yes.

00:22:24.120 --> 00:22:24.960
 Yes.

00:22:24.960 --> 00:22:26.820
 - Interference effects happen in, for example,

00:22:26.820 --> 00:22:29.420
 the double slit, which is this famous set up

00:22:29.420 --> 00:22:33.940
 where you have two slits with the backdrop being a wall

00:22:33.940 --> 00:22:36.460
 or some detector, and you send a particle through

00:22:36.460 --> 00:22:38.960
 one at a time, could be photon.

00:22:38.960 --> 00:22:42.700
 And then when you detect where the photon is on the screen,

00:22:42.700 --> 00:22:46.080
 after having repeated this experiment in series,

00:22:46.080 --> 00:22:48.340
 so you send one through and two at a time,

00:22:48.340 --> 00:22:50.060
 and you detect it, and then you send another one through,

00:22:50.060 --> 00:22:51.660
 and then you detect it again,

00:22:51.660 --> 00:22:53.900
 then you find that there's an interference pattern,

00:22:53.900 --> 00:22:54.740
 which wouldn't be there

00:22:54.740 --> 00:22:56.160
 if you closed either of the two slits.

00:22:56.160 --> 00:22:59.240
 - But what do you mean with an interference pattern?

00:22:59.240 --> 00:23:01.920
 - It means that there are places on the screen

00:23:01.920 --> 00:23:03.420
 where many photons arrive

00:23:03.420 --> 00:23:06.520
 and places where barely any or none arrive.

00:23:06.520 --> 00:23:07.920
 And they kind of, they come in fringes.

00:23:07.920 --> 00:23:12.320
 So it's like, you know, a lot, less, a lot.

00:23:12.320 --> 00:23:16.100
 And then again, much fewer or none, a lot.

00:23:16.100 --> 00:23:19.340
 And that keeps going on.

00:23:19.340 --> 00:23:21.820
 And that pattern is called an interference pattern

00:23:21.820 --> 00:23:23.680
 because the...

00:23:23.680 --> 00:23:26.160
 What's happening is that, for example,

00:23:26.160 --> 00:23:28.160
 in the case of the photon,

00:23:28.160 --> 00:23:30.800
 if you send it through the two slits,

00:23:30.800 --> 00:23:32.700
 it actually goes through both.

00:23:32.700 --> 00:23:33.540
 - Yes.

00:23:33.540 --> 00:23:36.340
 - And we'll get to why that's the case.

00:23:36.340 --> 00:23:38.060
 It goes through both.

00:23:38.060 --> 00:23:41.940
 And then there's an instance of the photon

00:23:41.940 --> 00:23:43.900
 going through the left one and one through the right one,

00:23:43.900 --> 00:23:45.840
 which then end up affecting each other.

00:23:45.840 --> 00:23:48.220
 So they end up interfering,

00:23:48.220 --> 00:23:49.960
 which just means they affect each other

00:23:49.960 --> 00:23:51.300
 just as they might.

00:23:51.300 --> 00:23:53.460
 It's a little bit similar to a classical way

00:23:53.460 --> 00:23:56.040
 of theory where if you have waves,

00:23:56.040 --> 00:23:57.880
 one of the things that can happen is

00:23:57.880 --> 00:24:00.440
 they can interact and then amplify each other.

00:24:00.440 --> 00:24:03.820
 Or if you have a trough and a peak,

00:24:03.820 --> 00:24:05.780
 then they could cancel.

00:24:05.780 --> 00:24:07.000
 And that's what's going on at the screen.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:09.740
 So some versions of the photon are amplifying each other

00:24:09.740 --> 00:24:13.440
 and some versions are interacting to cancel each other.

00:24:13.440 --> 00:24:16.100
 And as I said, if you do that many times,

00:24:16.100 --> 00:24:18.320
 each time you're sending a single photon through,

00:24:18.320 --> 00:24:20.540
 then you get this interference pattern.

00:24:20.540 --> 00:24:21.380
 - Yes.

00:24:21.380 --> 00:24:23.240
 - And the kind of the bizarre thing is if you close up,

00:24:23.240 --> 00:24:25.360
 close either of these two slits,

00:24:25.360 --> 00:24:26.420
 then it disappears.

00:24:26.420 --> 00:24:32.180
 So that indicates that something must be going

00:24:32.180 --> 00:24:35.620
 through the other slit to interact with the thing

00:24:35.620 --> 00:24:37.720
 that goes through the one that isn't closed,

00:24:37.720 --> 00:24:40.720
 so to give the pattern.

00:24:40.720 --> 00:24:43.300
 Otherwise you would still see the pattern

00:24:43.300 --> 00:24:45.900
 if only one slit were open, which we don't.

00:24:45.900 --> 00:24:47.240
 Again, the many worlds explanation is

00:24:47.240 --> 00:24:48.680
 there's two versions of the photon.

00:24:48.680 --> 00:24:49.980
 There's only ever one photon,

00:24:49.980 --> 00:24:53.020
 but the photon can consist of multiple instances

00:24:53.020 --> 00:24:55.620
 or versions or however you want to call it.

00:24:55.620 --> 00:24:57.240
 And they can affect each other.

00:24:57.240 --> 00:24:58.680
 They can interfere.

00:24:58.680 --> 00:25:00.700
 So we know from seeing the pattern

00:25:00.700 --> 00:25:02.940
 that the photon was in two places at once.

00:25:02.940 --> 00:25:05.360
 It took two paths at once.

00:25:05.360 --> 00:25:07.600
 And that is generally,

00:25:07.600 --> 00:25:10.020
 that's one of the main ways that we know about

00:25:10.020 --> 00:25:14.080
 quantum effects is that we see interference happening

00:25:14.080 --> 00:25:16.940
 in what are called generally interference experiments,

00:25:16.940 --> 00:25:18.720
 of which this is an instance.

00:25:18.720 --> 00:25:21.240
 - This effectively means that there are

00:25:22.800 --> 00:25:26.220
 billions if not an infinity of versions of you and I

00:25:26.220 --> 00:25:29.160
 in these different worlds.

00:25:29.160 --> 00:25:30.420
 Where are these worlds?

00:25:30.420 --> 00:25:32.380
 Like, wait, are they somewhere?

00:25:32.380 --> 00:25:33.300
 Like, can I go there?

00:25:33.300 --> 00:25:35.180
 Like, can I visit?

00:25:35.180 --> 00:25:40.100
 - So, firstly, there's not gonna be infinitely many.

00:25:40.100 --> 00:25:43.120
 There are reasons to believe that there is a bound

00:25:43.120 --> 00:25:44.980
 on how many different universes there can be.

00:25:44.980 --> 00:25:45.820
 - Interesting.

00:25:45.820 --> 00:25:50.220
 - That comes from, it's the so-called Bekenstein bound,

00:25:50.220 --> 00:25:52.580
 and it gives an argument for why in any

00:25:52.580 --> 00:25:55.140
 finite region there is an upper bound

00:25:55.140 --> 00:25:59.600
 to the amount of universes that can be there.

00:25:59.600 --> 00:26:02.880
 - Is that due to the number of interactions possible?

00:26:02.880 --> 00:26:04.960
 - It is due to the amount of information

00:26:04.960 --> 00:26:06.360
 you can store in a system.

00:26:06.360 --> 00:26:08.180
 So this is maybe a bit technical,

00:26:08.180 --> 00:26:12.580
 but the way to think about it is the different universes,

00:26:12.580 --> 00:26:15.680
 it should be the case that they do not interfere

00:26:15.680 --> 00:26:16.740
 with each other.

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:18.620
 They could in principle,

00:26:18.620 --> 00:26:22.000
 but we generally want them to evolve independently.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:24.560
 For that to be the case, they have to be orthogonal,

00:26:24.560 --> 00:26:28.480
 which is a technical term which I don't think I can explain.

00:26:28.480 --> 00:26:32.760
 But we generally want the universes

00:26:32.760 --> 00:26:35.300
 to be orthogonal to one another.

00:26:35.300 --> 00:26:36.240
 - Separate in a way.

00:26:36.240 --> 00:26:37.080
 - Yes.

00:26:37.080 --> 00:26:37.900
 - Yes, very distinct.

00:26:37.900 --> 00:26:40.200
 - Yes, yeah, they don't have overlap.

00:26:40.200 --> 00:26:44.000
 And the number of orthogonal states that you can have

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:47.940
 in a finite region of space is determined

00:26:47.940 --> 00:26:50.700
 by the maximum entropy in that region,

00:26:50.700 --> 00:26:51.780
 and the maximum entropy is bounded.

00:26:51.780 --> 00:26:55.380
 - Yes, so there's a limit capacity

00:26:55.380 --> 00:26:57.300
 of how much you can store, essentially.

00:26:57.300 --> 00:26:59.020
 - Yeah, exactly, yeah.

00:26:59.020 --> 00:27:01.920
 So, Bekenstein's bound gives an upper bound,

00:27:01.920 --> 00:27:02.760
 and that is a little bit technical.

00:27:02.760 --> 00:27:04.600
 I think that's the most technical thing we've said so far,

00:27:04.600 --> 00:27:09.600
 but the main idea is there is some bound

00:27:09.600 --> 00:27:14.600
 which determines things like how much information

00:27:14.600 --> 00:27:15.440
 you can store in a system,

00:27:15.440 --> 00:27:16.980
 and also how many universes there can be.

00:27:16.980 --> 00:27:18.500
 - Where are these universes?

00:27:18.500 --> 00:27:21.060
 - An enlarged space that we call Hilbert space.

00:27:21.060 --> 00:27:21.560
 - Yeah.

00:27:21.560 --> 00:27:25.260
 - And in some sense, the universe is,

00:27:25.260 --> 00:27:28.080
 it kind of depends on our views of space and time,

00:27:28.080 --> 00:27:32.900
 but in some sense, they are here in space.

00:27:32.900 --> 00:27:33.840
 - Yes.

00:27:33.840 --> 00:27:36.380
 - But they are in different points in Hilbert space.

00:27:36.380 --> 00:27:38.480
 So Hilbert space is this larger space

00:27:38.480 --> 00:27:39.900
 in which quantum states live.

00:27:39.900 --> 00:27:43.260
 - Mm, but it's a mathematical space, right?

00:27:43.260 --> 00:27:45.360
 Like, we're not talking about like,

00:27:45.360 --> 00:27:46.940
 necessarily like physical space,

00:27:46.940 --> 00:27:49.000
 like going to the moon or something, yeah.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:51.340
 - Yeah, no, it's a mathematical space,

00:27:51.340 --> 00:27:53.380
 and it's not the same thing as string theory

00:27:53.380 --> 00:27:54.740
 having multiple dimensions or anything.

00:27:54.740 --> 00:27:56.580
 - Yes.

00:27:56.580 --> 00:27:59.020
 - Everyone who does quantum physics is in agreement

00:27:59.020 --> 00:28:01.200
 that there is this thing called Hilbert space

00:28:01.200 --> 00:28:03.880
 in which the states of a quantum system live.

00:28:03.880 --> 00:28:06.680
 I think the best answer I can give is they live in Hilbert space.

00:28:06.680 --> 00:28:09.700
 Another way of saying it is that they exist in some sense,

00:28:09.700 --> 00:28:10.700
 they are just as real as we are,

00:28:10.700 --> 00:28:16.140
 because we also live in Hilbert space,

00:28:16.140 --> 00:28:17.620
 but they're just not where we are,

00:28:17.620 --> 00:28:18.940
 otherwise we would see them.

00:28:18.940 --> 00:28:21.120
 - So there's no way to interact with them?

00:28:21.120 --> 00:28:23.680
 Like once they're like orthogonal, as you said,

00:28:23.680 --> 00:28:24.780
 once they're like distinct,

00:28:24.780 --> 00:28:27.960
 like once the branch is distinct,

00:28:27.960 --> 00:28:29.900
 there's no way to interact with them, right?

00:28:29.900 --> 00:28:33.300
 - So maybe we should say that we have all these different terms

00:28:33.300 --> 00:28:34.560
 and they basically mean the same thing.

00:28:34.560 --> 00:28:38.300
 So we have the terms branches and universes and things like that.

00:28:38.300 --> 00:28:39.640
 - Universes, worlds, it's all the same thing.

00:28:39.640 --> 00:28:42.460
 - Yeah, it's all basically just parts of a quantum system

00:28:42.460 --> 00:28:45.160
 that don't really interact with other parts anymore

00:28:45.160 --> 00:28:47.740
 and evolve as if the other parts aren't there.

00:28:47.740 --> 00:28:50.900
 And sometimes also we have the connotation that we mean,

00:28:50.900 --> 00:28:55.900
 they are obeying semi-classical operations of motion.

00:28:55.900 --> 00:28:59.000
 They look like they're classical systems effectively,

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:02.520
 is what we might also mean, but at any rate,

00:29:02.520 --> 00:29:04.720
 so just to clarify some terminology,

00:29:04.720 --> 00:29:07.260
 it's always the case that they can interact in principle,

00:29:07.260 --> 00:29:08.140
 which is very hard.

00:29:08.140 --> 00:29:10.080
 - It's increasingly unlikely.

00:29:10.080 --> 00:29:12.020
 - Yeah, it's increasingly difficult essentially, yeah.

00:29:12.020 --> 00:29:17.020
 Like if, for example, in the photon experiment,

00:29:17.020 --> 00:29:19.680
 you're reinterfering a single photon

00:29:20.680 --> 00:29:23.760
 and that's quite a manageable task.

00:29:23.760 --> 00:29:28.720
 It's much more difficult to make a couple of photons

00:29:28.720 --> 00:29:30.160
 interfere with one another.

00:29:30.160 --> 00:29:32.100
 So they would interfere.

00:29:32.100 --> 00:29:34.040
 Well, maybe that's not the best example.

00:29:34.040 --> 00:29:36.480
 So let's say that the photon becomes entangled

00:29:36.480 --> 00:29:38.000
 with the environment somehow.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:41.940
 Then it's not just the photon that we need to reinterfere,

00:29:41.940 --> 00:29:43.600
 we also need to reinterfere the thing

00:29:43.600 --> 00:29:44.880
 that the photon is now entangled with.

00:29:44.880 --> 00:29:48.960
 - Yes, so we need to undo essentially our changes in a way.

00:29:48.960 --> 00:29:50.460
 - Yeah, and the reason for that is, roughly,

00:29:50.460 --> 00:29:53.640
 that for interference to happen,

00:29:53.640 --> 00:29:55.700
 the photon really should have taken both paths.

00:29:55.700 --> 00:29:57.560
 So one instance of the photon should take one path

00:29:57.560 --> 00:29:59.460
 and the other one should take the other one.

00:29:59.460 --> 00:30:04.460
 When the photon becomes entangled with the environment,

00:30:04.460 --> 00:30:07.460
 it essentially even traces of where it was.

00:30:07.460 --> 00:30:11.760
 And that means that there's now a definite answer

00:30:11.760 --> 00:30:14.900
 in that world where the photon was actually at,

00:30:14.900 --> 00:30:17.540
 which is information that you can't have

00:30:17.540 --> 00:30:19.460
 if the photon literally took both paths.

00:30:19.460 --> 00:30:20.240
 You can't say, well,

00:30:20.240 --> 00:30:21.580
 I know that the photon took this one,

00:30:21.580 --> 00:30:23.360
 but also it was in both.

00:30:23.360 --> 00:30:24.200
 - Yes.

00:30:24.200 --> 00:30:25.080
 - That's logically incoherent.

00:30:25.080 --> 00:30:30.220
 So instead, the photon shouldn't have any information.

00:30:30.220 --> 00:30:33.040
 I think it's sometimes called which-where information.

00:30:33.040 --> 00:30:36.500
 That means that either you erase that information

00:30:36.500 --> 00:30:37.580
 before the interference happens,

00:30:37.580 --> 00:30:41.760
 or the thing that was entangled with the photon

00:30:41.760 --> 00:30:43.700
 also interferes with the other version of itself

00:30:43.700 --> 00:30:45.680
 so that that information gets erased.

00:30:45.680 --> 00:30:47.300
 But somehow you need to get rid of that.

00:30:47.300 --> 00:30:50.020
 And it's hard because of course the photon and other parts

00:30:50.020 --> 00:30:52.980
 are constantly leaving ever more traces

00:30:52.980 --> 00:30:55.220
 in their environment of where they were.

00:30:55.220 --> 00:30:58.860
 So that means you have like an exponentially cascading

00:30:58.860 --> 00:31:00.200
 number of things to undo

00:31:00.200 --> 00:31:02.200
 before you can re-interfere the thing again.

00:31:02.200 --> 00:31:06.020
 - One of the, I guess one of the criticisms,

00:31:06.020 --> 00:31:06.860
 I guess you could say,

00:31:06.860 --> 00:31:09.220
 or like the common objections, let's say,

00:31:09.220 --> 00:31:13.320
 of many worlds is this idea of energy.

00:31:13.320 --> 00:31:14.760
 Because, well, if you're telling me

00:31:14.760 --> 00:31:18.060
 that we're now going to have all these parallel,

00:31:18.060 --> 00:31:18.900
 quote unquote,

00:31:19.800 --> 00:31:24.000
 universes, where does the energy come from?

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:26.040
 So we're just like duplicating each time?

00:31:26.040 --> 00:31:28.400
 Like, how is this actually possible?

00:31:28.400 --> 00:31:30.300
 - Yeah, so the funny thing is that intuitively

00:31:30.300 --> 00:31:31.420
 that seems very strange.

00:31:31.420 --> 00:31:32.880
 And actually, if you look at the mathematics,

00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:33.720
 it's much simpler.

00:31:33.720 --> 00:31:34.560
 - Yes.

00:31:34.560 --> 00:31:37.180
 - So in the case of it,

00:31:37.180 --> 00:31:40.320
 so people would expect that somehow many worlds

00:31:40.320 --> 00:31:42.480
 violates energy conservation.

00:31:42.480 --> 00:31:46.480
 And in fact, I think generally is a measurement which does,

00:31:46.480 --> 00:31:49.580
 because in...

00:31:49.580 --> 00:31:53.380
 in the many worlds picture,

00:31:53.380 --> 00:31:55.900
 you only ever have unitary evolution

00:31:55.900 --> 00:31:59.580
 and that preserves the energy of a system.

00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:01.080
 - What is unitary evolution?

00:32:01.080 --> 00:32:05.540
 - So we only ever have things like Schrodinger type evolution.

00:32:05.540 --> 00:32:07.820
 - So like linear, clean line.

00:32:07.820 --> 00:32:09.860
 - Yeah, reversible, all of the good stuff.

00:32:09.860 --> 00:32:10.700
 - Yeah.

00:32:10.700 --> 00:32:14.400
 - We like this, we like this.

00:32:14.400 --> 00:32:15.960
 - It's simple, it's beautiful.

00:32:15.960 --> 00:32:19.360
 - Yes, and that preserves the energy of a system.

00:32:19.360 --> 00:32:20.400
 - Yes.

00:32:20.400 --> 00:32:22.680
 - And measurement does not have that,

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:26.280
 and so you're not guaranteed to conserve the energy.

00:32:26.280 --> 00:32:27.120
 - Yes.

00:32:27.120 --> 00:32:28.960
 - Anyway, so there's one note.

00:32:28.960 --> 00:32:30.860
 The way I view it,

00:32:30.860 --> 00:32:34.680
 and I think lots of people who are into many worlds view

00:32:34.680 --> 00:32:38.740
 as well, is that this view of splitting the universe

00:32:38.740 --> 00:32:39.580
 is not right.

00:32:39.580 --> 00:32:42.260
 So it's not like you are splitting the universe.

00:32:42.260 --> 00:32:46.520
 It's more like every system already is a collection

00:32:46.520 --> 00:32:49.140
 of instances, all of which are,

00:32:49.140 --> 00:32:51.520
 are completely identical initially,

00:32:51.520 --> 00:32:54.440
 as kind of like a slap of the multiverse.

00:32:54.440 --> 00:32:57.980
 And then they, some of them become distinct.

00:32:57.980 --> 00:33:00.600
 So like maybe first it's this many,

00:33:00.600 --> 00:33:02.200
 and then some of them, you know.

00:33:02.200 --> 00:33:05.160
 - So we're constantly like slicing

00:33:05.160 --> 00:33:07.640
 the same block of energy in a way.

00:33:07.640 --> 00:33:09.640
 - Yes.

00:33:09.640 --> 00:33:12.900
 - And so, yeah, so it remains constant

00:33:12.900 --> 00:33:15.240
 across all of those branches,

00:33:15.240 --> 00:33:18.920
 but the branches themselves may have a smaller slice.

00:33:18.920 --> 00:33:20.340
 - Yeah, exactly, yeah.

00:33:20.340 --> 00:33:21.920
 So it's not like you're making mass.

00:33:21.920 --> 00:33:22.760
 - Yes.

00:33:22.760 --> 00:33:24.780
 - It's not like, oh, you, something happens,

00:33:24.780 --> 00:33:26.840
 something entangled, something entangles with another thing,

00:33:26.840 --> 00:33:29.620
 and now there's more mass because there's more universes.

00:33:29.620 --> 00:33:32.580
 It's more like there was already a certain amount of them,

00:33:32.580 --> 00:33:35.000
 which we can have a general measure of.

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.680
 - They were just identical, and now we're splitting them.

00:33:37.680 --> 00:33:38.680
 - Exactly, now they're, yeah.

00:33:38.680 --> 00:33:40.660
 So splitting, or they're branching.

00:33:40.660 --> 00:33:42.020
 - Yeah, slicing, yeah.

00:33:42.020 --> 00:33:44.680
 - All of that just means some portion of them

00:33:44.680 --> 00:33:47.060
 now do one thing and some portion are different

00:33:47.060 --> 00:33:48.040
 and do another.

00:33:48.040 --> 00:33:48.700
 - Yeah.

00:33:48.700 --> 00:33:52.260
 - So we're not creating any mass or energy in the process.

00:33:52.260 --> 00:33:55.580
 In fact, that is exactly what's conserved.

00:33:55.580 --> 00:33:57.420
 - A lot of your research is about time.

00:33:57.420 --> 00:33:58.620
 Is time real?

00:33:58.620 --> 00:34:01.000
 Does time actually exist?

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:01.840
 What is time?

00:34:01.840 --> 00:34:05.740
 - So some ways of viewing time or some notions of time

00:34:05.740 --> 00:34:07.760
 don't exist and others do.

00:34:07.760 --> 00:34:12.020
 And so I always like to say time doesn't exist.

00:34:12.020 --> 00:34:14.760
 I mean, it's a phrase that Julian Barber and others have used

00:34:14.760 --> 00:34:17.100
 and he wrote a very famous book,

00:34:17.100 --> 00:34:18.480
 which I highly recommend called

00:34:18.480 --> 00:34:19.480
 The Convention of Time.

00:34:19.480 --> 00:34:23.560
 And the argument in that book is that our general conception

00:34:23.560 --> 00:34:26.240
 of how time works is unnecessary.

00:34:26.240 --> 00:34:29.280
 And to explain what that means,

00:34:29.280 --> 00:34:33.560
 the convention of view is something like there is this parameter,

00:34:33.560 --> 00:34:37.460
 this number which represents time.

00:34:37.460 --> 00:34:39.100
 Maybe if you're thinking very classically,

00:34:39.100 --> 00:34:43.060
 then it's the same everywhere in the universe.

00:34:43.060 --> 00:34:44.920
 Of course, that can't be true because of special relativity,

00:34:44.920 --> 00:34:45.920
 but never mind that.

00:34:45.920 --> 00:34:48.260
 And it's kind of like God's clock.

00:34:48.260 --> 00:34:49.100
 Like God has a clock.

00:34:49.100 --> 00:34:52.060
 - It's like his wristwatch and like, yeah.

00:34:52.060 --> 00:34:53.920
 - And we cannot see it,

00:34:53.920 --> 00:34:55.700
 but we're invoking it because things are changing.

00:34:55.700 --> 00:34:57.260
 So things are changing and that means

00:34:57.260 --> 00:34:58.860
 that it's a different time now.

00:34:58.860 --> 00:35:01.080
 The actual things that we use to measure time,

00:35:01.080 --> 00:35:03.840
 like your watch, for example, and other things,

00:35:03.840 --> 00:35:06.760
 like the solar system is a thing,

00:35:06.760 --> 00:35:08.720
 which in some sense is a clock.

00:35:08.720 --> 00:35:11.160
 And the different positions of the planets

00:35:11.160 --> 00:35:16.160
 in the solar system tell us what time of year it is.

00:35:16.160 --> 00:35:18.040
 Maybe the seasons are different, things like that.

00:35:18.040 --> 00:35:20.820
 Those are things internal to the universe

00:35:20.820 --> 00:35:22.000
 which tell us what time is.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:25.280
 Whereas the kind of Newtonian view of time

00:35:25.280 --> 00:35:26.560
 is slightly different.

00:35:26.560 --> 00:35:30.100
 It's that, as I said, it's more ethereal.

00:35:30.100 --> 00:35:33.180
 There is some notion of time.

00:35:33.180 --> 00:35:34.440
 - Across everything.

00:35:34.440 --> 00:35:35.280
 - Across everything.

00:35:35.280 --> 00:35:38.200
 It's not something that you can necessarily see,

00:35:38.200 --> 00:35:39.040
 but it's there.

00:35:39.040 --> 00:35:40.100
 - And it's fixed everywhere.

00:35:40.100 --> 00:35:41.200
 - It's fixed everywhere, yeah.

00:35:41.200 --> 00:35:43.980
 - It's the same clock for wherever you go.

00:35:43.980 --> 00:35:44.820
 - Yes.

00:35:44.820 --> 00:35:47.820
 Again, that aspect of it was already no longer tenable,

00:35:47.820 --> 00:35:49.180
 with Einstein.

00:35:49.180 --> 00:35:51.020
 - Yes, relatively, yeah.

00:35:51.020 --> 00:35:51.860
 - But in some sense,

00:35:51.860 --> 00:35:54.780
 we don't need to concern ourselves with that so much.

00:35:54.780 --> 00:35:55.860
 The main thing that's weird is just,

00:35:55.860 --> 00:35:57.760
 it's not something that's observable within the universe.

00:35:57.760 --> 00:36:00.660
 We're just saying that there is something that's changing.

00:36:00.660 --> 00:36:03.560
 So this unobservable property of the universe is changing.

00:36:03.560 --> 00:36:06.260
 And because that thing is changing,

00:36:06.260 --> 00:36:07.620
 things around us are changing too.

00:36:07.620 --> 00:36:08.780
 So people are getting older,

00:36:08.780 --> 00:36:11.620
 but that's because time's passed, things like that.

00:36:11.620 --> 00:36:14.560
 And as I already kind of alluded to,

00:36:14.560 --> 00:36:17.600
 the thing that we actually use both

00:36:17.600 --> 00:36:18.960
 in everyday life and in science,

00:36:18.960 --> 00:36:22.720
 and I think also just nature more generally uses it

00:36:22.720 --> 00:36:23.600
 in some sense,

00:36:23.600 --> 00:36:27.180
 is time that is like internal to the universe.

00:36:27.180 --> 00:36:32.180
 So clocks are a way of seeing that some change has happened.

00:36:32.180 --> 00:36:35.440
 So there's some kind of periodic process in a clock

00:36:35.440 --> 00:36:38.200
 and you're counting how often that process has happened.

00:36:38.200 --> 00:36:39.160
 And that tells you, okay,

00:36:39.160 --> 00:36:44.160
 so the clock says X numbers of periods have elapsed.

00:36:44.160 --> 00:36:47.380
 I know now that other systems have changed

00:36:47.380 --> 00:36:48.220
 as a result as well,

00:36:48.220 --> 00:36:49.740
 because they're constantly undergoing

00:36:49.740 --> 00:36:51.700
 their own physical processes.

00:36:51.700 --> 00:36:55.540
 Like as your clock is ticking, your wristwatch,

00:36:55.540 --> 00:36:58.060
 the earth is also moving around the sun.

00:36:58.060 --> 00:37:01.040
 And we know that a certain number of ticks on your wristwatch

00:37:01.040 --> 00:37:04.520
 corresponds to a certain distance traveled through space

00:37:04.520 --> 00:37:06.880
 by the earth, things like that.

00:37:06.880 --> 00:37:11.880
 And it turns out even classical physics, as Julian showed,

00:37:11.880 --> 00:37:16.500
 that you can replace this ethereal notion of time,

00:37:16.500 --> 00:37:17.160
 this kind of like, okay,

00:37:17.160 --> 00:37:19.140
 the backdrop against which things happen,

00:37:19.140 --> 00:37:21.980
 which is itself, this is not really clearly physical.

00:37:21.980 --> 00:37:24.060
 You can replace that notion of time,

00:37:24.060 --> 00:37:27.300
 which is time as it exists internal to the universe.

00:37:27.300 --> 00:37:29.340
 Julian's way of doing it is very pretty.

00:37:29.340 --> 00:37:30.900
 What he does is he says,

00:37:30.900 --> 00:37:33.860
 you assume you just have celestial objects

00:37:33.860 --> 00:37:38.060
 and they are obeying Newton's equations of motion.

00:37:38.060 --> 00:37:40.780
 So the kind of gravity making them interact

00:37:40.780 --> 00:37:42.040
 and things like that.

00:37:42.040 --> 00:37:46.940
 And then adding a simple assumption that the energy

00:37:46.940 --> 00:37:49.880
 of the system is equal to zero.

00:37:49.880 --> 00:37:51.940
 So it's conserved and it's equal to zero.

00:37:51.940 --> 00:37:54.740
 It turns out that their positions

00:37:54.740 --> 00:37:56.880
 at any particular time are unique.

00:37:56.880 --> 00:37:58.680
 So you can kind of use their positions.

00:37:58.680 --> 00:38:00.680
 - To figure out what the time is.

00:38:00.680 --> 00:38:02.560
 - There exist counterparts of this in quantum mechanics,

00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:04.280
 which are very nice.

00:38:04.280 --> 00:38:07.940
 And I work on the quantum counterparts in particular.

00:38:07.940 --> 00:38:11.820
 So I think both in Julian's view and in my view,

00:38:11.820 --> 00:38:13.700
 as you rephrase that,

00:38:13.700 --> 00:38:15.000
 I think both in Julian's model,

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:16.720
 although not on Julian's view,

00:38:16.720 --> 00:38:19.960
 you get a kind of many-worlds picture again,

00:38:19.960 --> 00:38:22.840
 because to really get rid of time

00:38:22.840 --> 00:38:26.100
 is not quite enough to say that time's internal,

00:38:26.100 --> 00:38:27.580
 because you also,

00:38:27.580 --> 00:38:29.840
 if you still have to say,

00:38:29.840 --> 00:38:31.180
 well, these different configurations

00:38:31.180 --> 00:38:34.680
 are somehow coming about and ceasing to be,

00:38:34.680 --> 00:38:37.500
 then you need this external number again,

00:38:37.500 --> 00:38:40.760
 which is telling you what the state of the system is.

00:38:40.760 --> 00:38:43.600
 So instead, to really get rid of time,

00:38:43.600 --> 00:38:45.200
 one thing you can say is well,

00:38:46.500 --> 00:38:51.560
 all these configurations of the celestial objects, say,

00:38:51.560 --> 00:38:52.540
 exist together.

00:38:52.540 --> 00:38:53.940
 They all exist.

00:38:53.940 --> 00:38:58.940
 And the passage of time is just the change

00:38:58.940 --> 00:39:03.000
 of these celestial objects relative to you.

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:08.000
 But there is no external time to take into account.

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:10.700
 So they already exist.

00:39:10.700 --> 00:39:12.660
 The future and the past already exist.

00:39:12.660 --> 00:39:16.280
 You're just in a slice and you can see what time it is,

00:39:16.280 --> 00:39:18.720
 because the configurations are unique.

00:39:18.720 --> 00:39:20.640
 - The way we can measure time

00:39:20.640 --> 00:39:24.960
 is by observing the change in the world.

00:39:24.960 --> 00:39:25.800
 - Yes.

00:39:25.800 --> 00:39:27.720
 - And there's no fixed time.

00:39:27.720 --> 00:39:34.460
 And so each of our internal clocks in a way, like--

00:39:34.460 --> 00:39:35.900
 - Well, so that doesn't quite follow.

00:39:35.900 --> 00:39:38.940
 So again, that becomes more dependent

00:39:38.940 --> 00:39:40.840
 on what specific models that you're talking about.

00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:43.760
 So in Julian's model, time is fixed everywhere,

00:39:43.760 --> 00:39:46.060
 just by the position of all the celestial objects.

00:39:46.060 --> 00:39:47.120
 - Yes, yes, yes.

00:39:47.120 --> 00:39:50.740
 - So in that sense, again, it's the same everywhere.

00:39:50.740 --> 00:39:51.580
 - Yes.

00:39:51.580 --> 00:39:54.500
 - And, but the main thing about it is that it's internal.

00:39:54.500 --> 00:39:57.800
 It's like you have this internal label of what the time is,

00:39:57.800 --> 00:39:59.300
 because you can look at the celestial objects and say,

00:39:59.300 --> 00:40:00.520
 okay, well, these are their positions.

00:40:00.520 --> 00:40:04.720
 And you can kind of, you can glue them back together,

00:40:04.720 --> 00:40:05.820
 knowing the laws of physics,

00:40:05.820 --> 00:40:09.860
 you know how to line them up, the sequence.

00:40:09.860 --> 00:40:14.860
 And it's that understanding that allows you to replace

00:40:15.840 --> 00:40:20.840
 this unphysical idea of time with internal labels

00:40:20.840 --> 00:40:24.220
 of what time it is inside the universe.

00:40:24.220 --> 00:40:27.160
 So it's kind of like, we want to get rid

00:40:27.160 --> 00:40:31.280
 of this weird background structure that we can't observe.

00:40:31.280 --> 00:40:32.340
 Like the theory already tells us,

00:40:32.340 --> 00:40:35.540
 we can't observe this ethereal notion of time,

00:40:35.540 --> 00:40:37.580
 this absolute time, as Newton called it.

00:40:37.580 --> 00:40:38.700
 So instead, we should just look at the things

00:40:38.700 --> 00:40:40.880
 that we can observe, like for example,

00:40:40.880 --> 00:40:43.920
 your clock or the positions of celestial bodies.

00:40:43.920 --> 00:40:45.620
 That is both much more based in observation,

00:40:45.620 --> 00:40:49.020
 and much more satisfying theoretically.

00:40:49.020 --> 00:40:53.340
 And it leads again to something like a many worlds view.

00:40:53.340 --> 00:40:58.100
 So in particular, we talk mainly about

00:40:58.100 --> 00:41:01.540
 Julian's classical setup, which I like a lot.

00:41:01.540 --> 00:41:05.200
 And there is a counterpart to this in quantum mechanics,

00:41:05.200 --> 00:41:07.600
 where it's literally many worlds.

00:41:07.600 --> 00:41:12.600
 So you assume that you're in the universe,

00:41:15.400 --> 00:41:19.620
 you have the description of the universe or the multiverse.

00:41:19.620 --> 00:41:24.620
 And you say, well, it's completely stationary.

00:41:24.620 --> 00:41:28.400
 We want to get rid of this idea that things are changing

00:41:28.400 --> 00:41:30.660
 relative to the external time parameter,

00:41:30.660 --> 00:41:32.280
 relative to the absolute time.

00:41:32.280 --> 00:41:34.560
 So let's just assume everything is stationary.

00:41:34.560 --> 00:41:36.060
 And now let's carve the world up into something

00:41:36.060 --> 00:41:39.100
 we're going to call a clock and the rest of the universe.

00:41:39.100 --> 00:41:44.100
 And they're not interacting, it's an important assumption.

00:41:45.180 --> 00:41:49.160
 And then what you say is, well, these two systems

00:41:49.160 --> 00:41:50.840
 are entangled with one another.

00:41:50.840 --> 00:41:54.760
 So that, for example, when the clock says it's 3:00 PM,

00:41:54.760 --> 00:41:59.940
 then the rest of the universe is doing a particular thing.

00:41:59.940 --> 00:42:02.680
 And then when the clock says it's 3:05,

00:42:02.680 --> 00:42:05.180
 then the rest of the universe looks slightly different.

00:42:05.180 --> 00:42:09.560
 And when it's 3:10, then the rest of the universe

00:42:09.560 --> 00:42:11.480
 looks slightly different again.

00:42:11.480 --> 00:42:14.960
 In such a way that if you keep conditioning on the clock,

00:42:14.960 --> 00:42:16.340
 the rest of the universe evolves

00:42:16.340 --> 00:42:18.180
 according to the laws of motion that we know.

00:42:18.180 --> 00:42:19.000
 - Yes.

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:24.000
 - And then again, you have time coming from a time.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:25.660
 So you have a notion of time

00:42:25.660 --> 00:42:28.580
 that comes from a timeless description in that case.

00:42:28.580 --> 00:42:31.580
 And it's a many worlds view because the different universes

00:42:31.580 --> 00:42:33.080
 are now just the different moments in time

00:42:33.080 --> 00:42:36.120
 and they all exist together in a kind of block

00:42:36.120 --> 00:42:38.660
 in what are sometimes called the block universe.

00:42:38.660 --> 00:42:40.420
 - There's a clock.

00:42:40.420 --> 00:42:42.080
 - Yeah, so you assume that there is a clock.

00:42:42.080 --> 00:42:44.740
 The model assumes there is such a thing as a clock.

00:42:44.740 --> 00:42:46.820
 - Is this like a theoretical clock

00:42:46.820 --> 00:42:48.080
 or is this actually like a real clock?

00:42:48.080 --> 00:42:48.900
 - Yeah, so, okay.

00:42:48.900 --> 00:42:52.280
 So one of the things that I am quite happy with having done

00:42:52.280 --> 00:42:56.360
 is, so this model is due to Page and Woodhurst.

00:42:56.360 --> 00:42:57.200
 - Yes, yes.

00:42:57.200 --> 00:42:59.240
 This is an old model by the way, right?

00:42:59.240 --> 00:43:00.700
 This is like many decades ago.

00:43:00.700 --> 00:43:01.540
 I think in the '70s.

00:43:01.540 --> 00:43:02.400
 - I think in the '80s.

00:43:02.400 --> 00:43:03.240
 - Oh, '80s, '80s.

00:43:03.240 --> 00:43:04.080
 Okay, yeah, yeah.

00:43:04.080 --> 00:43:05.540
 - And a very nice model.

00:43:05.540 --> 00:43:07.740
 One of the assumptions that went into it is,

00:43:07.740 --> 00:43:08.580
 as you're writing the point out,

00:43:08.580 --> 00:43:10.500
 it's kind of strange is that there's no interactions

00:43:10.500 --> 00:43:13.520
 between the clock and the rest of the universe.

00:43:13.520 --> 00:43:14.520
 So it kind of feels,

00:43:14.520 --> 00:43:16.280
 if you again, 'cause now,

00:43:16.280 --> 00:43:18.380
 I was saying, well, you can look at your watch,

00:43:18.380 --> 00:43:19.820
 but this is not a clock you can look at.

00:43:19.820 --> 00:43:20.660
 - Yes.

00:43:20.660 --> 00:43:21.780
 - And since then,

00:43:21.780 --> 00:43:23.980
 so I think what has happened is that initially,

00:43:23.980 --> 00:43:27.640
 people kind of were very critical of this model.

00:43:27.640 --> 00:43:30.520
 It went out of vogue and now it's in vogue again.

00:43:30.520 --> 00:43:31.860
 And people worked on it a lot.

00:43:31.860 --> 00:43:34.480
 One of the things they've done is shown that

00:43:34.480 --> 00:43:36.140
 even when there's interactions,

00:43:36.140 --> 00:43:39.320
 you can still get these,

00:43:39.320 --> 00:43:40.480
 let's call them Page-Woodhurst states.

00:43:40.480 --> 00:43:42.840
 So you can still get timeless descriptions,

00:43:42.840 --> 00:43:44.300
 even when there are certain kinds of

00:43:44.300 --> 00:43:45.780
 interactions, not general kinds of interactions,

00:43:45.780 --> 00:43:47.200
 but certain kinds of interactions between the clock

00:43:47.200 --> 00:43:48.780
 and the rest of the universe.

00:43:48.780 --> 00:43:50.400
 And building on that,

00:43:50.400 --> 00:43:54.520
 Simona Rijovec and I showed that,

00:43:54.520 --> 00:43:56.760
 in particular, you can measure the clock

00:43:56.760 --> 00:43:58.240
 without disturbing the model.

00:43:58.240 --> 00:44:01.740
 So you still have the timeless view emerging from it.

00:44:01.740 --> 00:44:04.800
 So you still have different universes being different times

00:44:04.800 --> 00:44:11.040
 and the clock giving you the equations of motion

00:44:11.040 --> 00:44:13.320
 that were used to all the good stuff.

00:44:13.320 --> 00:44:14.080
 But the only thing that's different is that,

00:44:14.080 --> 00:44:15.120
 you can actually observe it.

00:44:15.120 --> 00:44:17.520
 So you can say, okay, well, I can see, for example,

00:44:17.520 --> 00:44:19.380
 - It won't affect the system.

00:44:19.380 --> 00:44:21.560
 - So you, yeah, you won't disturb it in such a way

00:44:21.560 --> 00:44:23.280
 that the clock no longer functions as a clock.

00:44:23.280 --> 00:44:24.120
 - Okay.

00:44:24.120 --> 00:44:26.080
 - I think that's the technical way of putting it

00:44:26.080 --> 00:44:28.560
 or the technically correct way of putting it anyway.

00:44:28.560 --> 00:44:30.080
 So that means that, for example,

00:44:30.080 --> 00:44:32.000
 according to this extended model,

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:35.720
 your wristwatch is really a clock in this sense.

00:44:35.720 --> 00:44:38.720
 So you can look at it and you provide it

00:44:38.720 --> 00:44:39.620
 that you don't destroy it.

00:44:39.620 --> 00:44:40.680
 You don't do certain things to it

00:44:40.680 --> 00:44:43.860
 that completely ruin it in its function as a clock.

00:44:43.860 --> 00:44:46.640
 You can observe it and measure the time.

00:44:46.640 --> 00:44:48.440
 Yeah, that's one of the ways

00:44:48.440 --> 00:44:50.600
 in which the model has been advanced.

00:44:50.600 --> 00:44:54.600
 So it's becoming ever more physical, I would say,

00:44:54.600 --> 00:44:56.280
 and we have an ever better understanding

00:44:56.280 --> 00:44:58.040
 of how these clocks should work.

00:44:58.040 --> 00:45:00.340
 So I think it's fair to say that your wristwatch

00:45:00.340 --> 00:45:02.100
 counts as a clock in this sense.

00:45:02.100 --> 00:45:07.100
 - So time isn't just like a sequence of these universes

00:45:07.100 --> 00:45:10.140
 or like, how do we best like recap it?

00:45:10.140 --> 00:45:13.640
 Like if I had to explain this to my mom or something,

00:45:13.640 --> 00:45:15.420
 who is not a physicist,

00:45:15.420 --> 00:45:17.900
 what is the best way to like phrase this,

00:45:17.900 --> 00:45:19.840
 to think about time then

00:45:19.840 --> 00:45:21.640
 from this like quantum mechanical perspective?

00:45:21.640 --> 00:45:25.300
 - I think the best way to view it is that in this view,

00:45:25.300 --> 00:45:29.860
 each moment of time is equally real.

00:45:29.860 --> 00:45:34.000
 And so the past exists, the future exists,

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:35.320
 they're not coming into existence.

00:45:35.320 --> 00:45:37.280
 I think that the typical view is they come into existence

00:45:37.280 --> 00:45:39.540
 and then they cease to exist instantly.

00:45:39.540 --> 00:45:41.140
 And there's this species present,

00:45:41.140 --> 00:45:43.420
 which is constantly moving forward.

00:45:43.420 --> 00:45:48.080
 That's not what's happening according to this understanding.

00:45:48.080 --> 00:45:52.000
 What's happening instead is you're finding yourself

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:54.400
 in these different universes,

00:45:54.400 --> 00:45:58.380
 but they already, like the universes are all there.

00:45:58.380 --> 00:45:59.640
 If we were to say,

00:45:59.640 --> 00:46:02.440
 what was the state of the universe like five minutes ago?

00:46:02.440 --> 00:46:05.440
 Well, then there is a world that exists,

00:46:05.440 --> 00:46:08.900
 which is the state of the universe five minutes ago,

00:46:08.900 --> 00:46:10.280
 where we were talking.

00:46:10.280 --> 00:46:13.200
 And in some sense, we're still talking.

00:46:13.200 --> 00:46:17.200
 We're still, us of five minutes ago are still having

00:46:17.200 --> 00:46:20.860
 that conversation five minutes ago, if that makes sense.

00:46:20.860 --> 00:46:24.420
 - So it's basically all happening at the same time.

00:46:24.420 --> 00:46:27.620
 - Yes, so yeah, it's hard to find a good terminology

00:46:27.620 --> 00:46:29.500
 for this 'cause at the same time, it's kind of a misnomer,

00:46:29.500 --> 00:46:34.500
 but it's kind of like maybe an analogy that is helpful is,

00:46:34.500 --> 00:46:37.920
 so perhaps this will go on YouTube,

00:46:37.920 --> 00:46:41.260
 perhaps this will go on a podcasting app.

00:46:41.260 --> 00:46:42.980
 When you're listening to it, you're hearing,

00:46:42.980 --> 00:46:45.140
 you're hearing a particular moment from the interview,

00:46:45.140 --> 00:46:48.320
 but the moments are already all there.

00:46:48.320 --> 00:46:50.440
 Like you can go to any part in the interview

00:46:50.440 --> 00:46:52.700
 and the recording is already completely,

00:46:52.700 --> 00:46:53.740
 it's already been recorded.

00:46:53.740 --> 00:46:57.140
 It's not like our voices are coming in and out of existence.

00:46:57.140 --> 00:47:00.680
 They are already completely present

00:47:00.680 --> 00:47:04.600
 in the recording of the conversation or like with books.

00:47:04.600 --> 00:47:07.860
 I mean, a story already exists before you read it.

00:47:07.860 --> 00:47:11.320
 You're just on page 10 and you're gonna go to page 11,

00:47:11.320 --> 00:47:12.760
 but page 10 still exists.

00:47:12.760 --> 00:47:15.720
 And you can reread it and the same things will happen again.

00:47:15.720 --> 00:47:17.840
 And that's kind of the picture of the universe

00:47:17.840 --> 00:47:18.680
 that this gives you.

00:47:18.680 --> 00:47:20.560
 - What is happening in the future already exists.

00:47:20.560 --> 00:47:22.540
 What is happening in the past already exists.

00:47:22.540 --> 00:47:25.520
 So how do we then think of free will

00:47:25.520 --> 00:47:30.520
 and your free agency in that context?

00:47:30.520 --> 00:47:33.420
 - The future might already exist, but we can't predict it.

00:47:33.420 --> 00:47:35.760
 We can't predict from the current state of the universe

00:47:35.760 --> 00:47:37.720
 what the future will entail.

00:47:37.720 --> 00:47:39.080
 - And I'm guessing you can affect

00:47:39.080 --> 00:47:41.980
 in which branch you end up in.

00:47:41.980 --> 00:47:42.540
 Is that right? - In some sense.

00:47:42.540 --> 00:47:48.500
 If you have to explain why the story unfolds as it does,

00:47:48.500 --> 00:47:50.460
 you have to account for people's motives,

00:47:50.460 --> 00:47:52.420
 their actions, their ideas.

00:47:52.420 --> 00:47:56.140
 And even though the book is already there in full,

00:47:56.140 --> 00:47:59.880
 the reason why, for example, a hero defeats a villain

00:47:59.880 --> 00:48:02.340
 might still be because of the various things

00:48:02.340 --> 00:48:03.800
 he did throughout the book.

00:48:03.800 --> 00:48:06.100
 So his actions had consequences,

00:48:06.100 --> 00:48:08.700
 even in the deterministic universe.

00:48:08.700 --> 00:48:10.700
 If every time you watch the movie,

00:48:10.700 --> 00:48:12.320
 it had a completely different outcome,

00:48:12.320 --> 00:48:17.940
 that would not really be congruous or something

00:48:17.940 --> 00:48:21.520
 with this idea that his actions have results,

00:48:21.520 --> 00:48:24.080
 that he's doing something in the world.

00:48:24.080 --> 00:48:27.340
 So we can have explanations of people and stories

00:48:27.340 --> 00:48:29.380
 and why their actions were good

00:48:29.380 --> 00:48:32.220
 and why they affected the world in certain ways.

00:48:32.220 --> 00:48:34.320
 And I think the same is true for us,

00:48:34.320 --> 00:48:36.600
 even though we live in a deterministic universe.

00:48:36.600 --> 00:48:37.960
 - Actions have consequences

00:48:37.960 --> 00:48:40.040
 and they do still need to be logical.

00:48:40.040 --> 00:48:42.100
 If I jump from the fifth floor,

00:48:42.100 --> 00:48:44.560
 to the grounds, I will get hurt, right?

00:48:44.560 --> 00:48:46.740
 There's no universe where I won't get hurt.

00:48:46.740 --> 00:48:47.860
 Like I'm very few.

00:48:47.860 --> 00:48:50.180
 - Yeah, it's a bit like, okay,

00:48:50.180 --> 00:48:52.320
 if we think that free will doesn't exist

00:48:52.320 --> 00:48:54.860
 and we just lie down on the couch forever,

00:48:54.860 --> 00:48:56.020
 well then we won't do anything.

00:48:56.020 --> 00:49:00.980
 So, you know, lying down on the couch had results,

00:49:00.980 --> 00:49:02.780
 predictable results, maybe even.

00:49:02.780 --> 00:49:06.860
 And whereas undertaking certain actions

00:49:06.860 --> 00:49:08.140
 will have different results.

00:49:08.140 --> 00:49:09.220
 And we know that in advance,

00:49:09.220 --> 00:49:10.840
 we have a choice to sit on the couch

00:49:10.840 --> 00:49:11.880
 or not to sit on the couch.

00:49:11.880 --> 00:49:16.880
 And our actions still have consequences,

00:49:16.880 --> 00:49:17.960
 even if it's determined.

00:49:17.960 --> 00:49:19.960
 I mean, kind of because it's deterministic,

00:49:19.960 --> 00:49:21.680
 our actions have consequences.

00:49:21.680 --> 00:49:24.080
 I mean, I don't have a full theory of free will,

00:49:24.080 --> 00:49:27.600
 but this is roughly how I think about it.

00:49:27.600 --> 00:49:30.540
 - Yeah, and it's an active area of research, right?

00:49:30.540 --> 00:49:32.500
 - Yeah, it's not something I work on.

00:49:32.500 --> 00:49:34.880
 But if you were to ask me as a physicist,

00:49:34.880 --> 00:49:36.380
 how do you think you can incorporate it with that?

00:49:36.380 --> 00:49:37.500
 It would be something like this.

00:49:37.500 --> 00:49:38.860
 - Yes, that makes sense.

00:49:38.860 --> 00:49:40.700
 Perfect, well, thank you so much for your time.

00:49:40.700 --> 00:49:41.660
 This was a pleasure.

00:49:41.660 --> 00:49:43.280
 and let's do this again soon.

00:49:43.280 --> 00:49:43.880
 Sounds good.

00:49:43.880 --> 00:49:44.580
 Thanks for having me.

00:49:44.580 --> 00:49:44.840
 Sounds great.

00:49:44.840 --> 00:49:45.560
 Thank you.

